    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Primula sulphurea are infusion, tincture, tea, salve, and ointment. Infusion and tea are prepared by steeping the flowers in hot water, extracting the flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. The tincture is a concentrated liquid extract of the flowers, often used in homeopathic and herbal medicine, which is made by soaking the plant material in a solvent such as ethanol or glycerin. Salve and ointment preparations involve mixing the infused oil of the flowers with other ingredients like beeswax and essential oils, creating topical applications that can be used to treat skin irritations and wounds. These preparations are used to harness the antimicrobial, antiseptic, and anti-inflammatory properties of Primula sulphurea, making it a valuable remedy for various health issues.",
